:","habitational name from the county of Cornwall, which is named with the Old English tribal name <i>Cornwealas</i>. This is from <i>Kernow</i> (the term that the Cornish used to refer to themselves, a word of uncertain etymology, perhaps connected with a Celtic element meaning ‘horn, headland’), + Old English <i>wealas</i> ‘strangers, foreigners’, the term used by the Anglo-Saxons for British-speaking people.","variant of   Cornwell  ."]},{"name":"Cornish","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name for someone from the county of Cornwall, from Middle English <i>Cornish</i>, <i>Cornysh</i> formed on the analogy of <i>English</i>, which was usually Normanized as <i>Corneys</i>. Not surprisingly, the surname is common in adjacent Devon, but it is also established as far afield as Suffolk and London."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":4,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":49,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"htt